This section provides the MP CSCI states and operational modes. MP CSCI operations are decomposed into three states: 1) OFF, 2) Limited Processing, and 3) Operational. These MP CSCI operational states map to the MP hardware OFF, Battery, and DC Bus Available, states, respectively.

The MP CSCI State Transition Diagram is shown in Figure x. The MP CSCI operational modes: 1) No MP Operation, 2) Normal MP Operation, and Single MP Operation are dependent on Processor Select Switch position and individual MP health and failure status and align to the following aircraft level MP hardware modes: 1) Non Operational, 2) Dual Processor, and 3) Single Processor. Common sub modes between the MP hardware and MP CSCI operations are as indicated in the States & Modes availability table, see Table x and are further described below.

The Apache Longbow aircraft utilizes two MPs. When the MP CSCI is operating in the Limited Processing or Operational state, the active sub mode depends on the operational mode. The sub modes are coordinated between the two MPs as only one MP can op
erate in the Primary sub mode.
Each sub mode is further described below:

: In this sub mode, the MP CSCI has overall control of avionics operations and is the MP that performs those functions which are redundant between the two MPs. These redundant functions include tasks such as acting as MUX Bus Controller (BC) on all MUX channels, controlling the aircraft engines and most other aircraft subsystems, and enabling its “shared” direct outputs.
Is Bus Controller (BC) on MUX channels 1, 2, 3, and 5,
MP2 controls the left and right pilot MPDs,
Enables and controls the MPD serial lines to both MPDs it is controlling,
Disables the serial lines to the two MPDs it is not controlling,
Enables and controls discrete and analog outputs,
Enables and controls the LMP, pilot UFD, and CPG UFD serial lines,

: The MP which is not the Primary MP is designated the “Secondary” MP. It is possible to have two Secondary MPs (e.g., temporarily during start–up), but it is not possible to have two Primary MPs. When possible, both MPs share information in order to keep the Secondary MP updated as to the current aircraft status and sub modes, and to coordinate processor switchovers
(i.e., the Secondary MP becomes the Primary MP and the Primary MP becomes the Secondary MP) based on the relative health of the two MPs.
Is a Remote Terminal (RT) and Bus Monitor (BM) on MUX channels 1, 2, 3, and 5,
MP2 controls the left and right pilot MPDs,
Enables and controls the serial lines to the 2 MPDs it is controlling,
Disables the serial lines to the two MPDs it is not controlling,
Disables the LMP, pilot UFD, and CPG UFD serial lines,
In this sub mode, the MP CSCI has overall control of avionics operations. The other MP is in the NOOP sub mode.

This mode occurs when one of the MPs is not capable of filling its roll. This can be caused by external factors such as damaged I/O wiring, or by internal issues such as an MP failure of some sort. In this mode, only one MP is driving all displays, and controlling the avionics.
Is Bus Controller (BC) on MUX channels 1, 2, 3, and 5,

Controls all four MPDs. The pilot and CPG left MPDs display the same video and symbology, while the pilot and CPG right MPDs display the same video and symbology, however the left and right MPD displays can display independent video and symbology.
Enables and controls the serial lines to all four MPDs,
Enables and controls discrete and analog outputs,
Enables and controls the LMP, pilot UFD, and CPG UFD serial lines,

: This sub mode is selected by the crew via the processor select switch and allows the crew to override the MSM.MPCC mode determination. In this condition, the other MP is commanded to the DISABLED mode (see below).
Is Bus Controller (BC) on MUX channels 1, 2, 3, and 5,

Controls all 4 MPDs. The pilot and CPG left MPDs display the same video and symbology, while the pilot and CPG right MPDs display the same video and symbology, however the left and right MPD displays can display independent video and symbology.
Enables and controls the serial lines to all 4 MPDs,
Enables and controls discrete and analog outputs,
Enables and controls the LMP, pilot UFD, and CPG UFD serial lines,
: The MP operates as a Remote Terminal (RT) on MUX channels 1, 2, 3, and 5,
: All MP I/O is disabled. In this mode the MP is unusable because it is incapable of controlling any external devices. This mode is entered when the crew
selects to disable the LRU by selecting the other MP via the processor select switch.

This sub mode provides transition between the OFF and Battery or AC Power states. If both engine throttles are off, a ground startup is performed. If the aircraft is determined to be in the air (see next section) or either engine throttle is not in the off position, an in-flight startup is performed.
